{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17531472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17531472"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:14:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:14:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14600"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14600","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14600"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.43,0.1,0.06,0.34]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7293"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57314"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7293","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7293"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14600"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42773"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"3737"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17829"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44314"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57314","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57314"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for routine follow-up. She reports occasional headaches and burning pain in her hands and feet over the past three months. She has no fever, night sweats, weight loss, or other symptoms. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is a non-smoker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The spleen tip is just palpable on deep inspiration. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaemoglobin 142 g/L (115-160)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite cell count 11.2 x 10\u2079/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPlatelet count 850 x 10\u2079/L (150-400)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EJAK2 V617F mutation testing is positive.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chronic myeloid leukaemia","Essential thrombocythaemia","Primary myelofibrosis","Reactive thrombocytosis","Polycythaemia vera"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suggestive of a myeloproliferative neoplasm, specifically \u003Cstrong\u003Eessential thrombocythaemia\u003C/strong\u003E. The key findings include marked thrombocytosis (platelet count \u0026gt;450 x 10\u2079/L), presence of JAK2 V617F mutation, and characteristic symptoms including erythromelalgia (burning pain in hands and feet) and headaches. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic myeloid leukaemia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a much higher white cell count, often \u0026gt;50 x 10\u2079/L, and would be characterised by the presence of BCR::ABL1 fusion gene rather than JAK2 mutation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary myelofibrosis\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with significant constitutional symptoms, marked splenomegaly, anaemia, and characteristic tear-drop shaped red cells on blood film. While it can also be JAK2 positive, the clinical picture here is not consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReactive thrombocytosis\u003C/strong\u003E occurs secondary to inflammation, infection, or iron deficiency. It would not be associated with JAK2 mutation or erythromelalgia, and platelet counts typically normalise when the underlying condition is treated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolycythaemia vera\u003C/strong\u003E, while also JAK2 mutation-positive in most cases, is characterised by elevated haemoglobin and haematocrit, which are normal in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Essential thrombocythaemia is characterised by a persistent platelet count \u003E450 x 10\u2079/L with JAK2 V617F mutation in approximately 50-60% of cases.","The clinical features of essential thrombocythaemia include erythromelalgia, headaches, and mild splenomegaly.","The diagnostic criteria for essential thrombocythaemia include elevated platelets, bone marrow features, and presence of JAK2, CALR, or MPL mutation."],"references":["Tefferi A, Vannucchi AM, Barbui T. Essential thrombocythemia: 2024 update on diagnosis, risk stratification, and management. Am J Hematol. 2024;99(4):697-718. doi:10.1002/ajh.27216"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42773"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14600"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42773","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42773"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-25T19:10:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-25T19:11:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7293"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57314"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"3737","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3737"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Essential thrombocythaemia","